    <h1 style="text-align:center;">Does Medicare Cover Dental in Vernal, Utah?</h1>
    
        <p>One of the most common Medicare questions from Vernal residents is about dental coverage. The short answer: Original Medicare (Parts A and B) provides almost no dental coverage. However, there are several ways to get dental benefits through Medicare.</p>

        <h2>What Original Medicare Covers (and Doesn't)</h2>
        <p>Original Medicare Part A covers dental care only when it is medically necessary as part of a covered hospital procedure — for example, jaw reconstruction after an injury. Part B does not cover routine dental care: no cleanings, fillings, crowns, dentures, bridges, extractions, or root canals. This gap surprises many new Medicare enrollees.</p>

        <h2>Medicare Advantage Dental Benefits</h2>
        <p>Most Medicare Advantage plans in the Vernal area include dental benefits. These typically cover two preventive cleanings and exams per year, X-rays, fillings, and sometimes more comprehensive services like crowns, root canals, and dentures. Coverage limits vary by plan — some cap annual dental benefits at $1,000–$2,000, while others offer more. We compare dental benefits alongside medical coverage when reviewing plans.</p>

        <h2>Standalone Dental Plans</h2>
        <p>If you have Original Medicare with Medigap, you can add a standalone dental plan. Several insurers offer dental-specific policies in Utah. Premiums typically range from $20 to $50 per month. Some plans have waiting periods for major services. We can help you evaluate whether a standalone dental plan or a Medicare Advantage plan with dental makes more sense for your situation.</p>

        <h2>Dental Providers in the Uintah Basin</h2>
        <p>Vernal has multiple dental offices, but not all participate in every plan's network. Before enrolling in any plan for dental benefits, confirm that your preferred dentist accepts the coverage. We help verify this during the plan comparison process.</p>

